<subSubSection box="[151,274,1539,1565]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,640,1503,1565]" box="[151,274,1539,1565]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">
(
<figureCitation box="[159,264,1539,1565]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1361,1385]" captionTargetBox="[152,1430,316,1325]" captionTargetId="figure-66@2.[151,1437,306,1334]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Sulcolotis threadis Liu et Wang sp. n.: a) head, ventral; b. head, clypeus; c. antenna; d. labrum; e. left mandible; f. right mandible; g. maxilla; h. labium; i. prothorax, ventral; j. meso- and metaventrite; k. spermatheca; l. female genitalia." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6876469" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6876469/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">Figs 1a–l</figureCitation>
)
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="77" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,1611,2033]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,274,1611,1637]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
This species can be easily separated from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Miyatake" authorityYear="1994" box="[748,887,1612,1638]" class="Insecta" family="Coccinellidae" genus="Sulcolotis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="seminigra">
<emphasis box="[748,887,1612,1638]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">S. seminigra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the following characters: elytron yellow, with a large black spot situated at 1/3 elytral length to base. In 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Miyatake" authorityYear="1994" box="[802,942,1648,1674]" class="Insecta" family="Coccinellidae" genus="Sulcolotis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="seminigra">
<emphasis box="[802,942,1648,1674]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">S. seminigra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, elytra are black in basal half and yellow in apical half, without dark spots. It is also similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Liu &amp; Wang &amp; Guo &amp; Chen &amp; Wang" authorityYear="2022" box="[713,807,1683,1710]" class="Insecta" family="Coccinellidae" genus="Sulcolotis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ovalis">
<emphasis box="[713,807,1683,1710]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">S. ovalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but can be separated from the latter by the bright yellow head and penis guide nearly as long as parameres. In 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Liu &amp; Wang &amp; Guo &amp; Chen &amp; Wang" authorityYear="2022" box="[753,848,1719,1746]" class="Insecta" family="Coccinellidae" genus="Sulcolotis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ovalis">
<emphasis box="[753,848,1719,1746]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">S. ovalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, head is reddish brown and penis guide shorter than parameres.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="78" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,1611,2033]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,1791,1817]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">Description.</emphasis>
TL: 
<quantity box="[392,551,1791,1817]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.9" metricValueMax="3.07" metricValueMin="2.73" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" unit="mm" value="2.9" valueMax="3.07" valueMin="2.73">2.73–3.07mm</quantity>
, TW: 
<quantity box="[615,774,1791,1818]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.41" metricValueMax="2.52" metricValueMin="2.3" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" unit="mm" value="2.41" valueMax="2.52" valueMin="2.3">2.30–2.52mm</quantity>
, TH: 
<quantity box="[833,991,1791,1818]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.535" metricValueMax="1.56" metricValueMin="1.51" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" unit="mm" value="1.535" valueMax="1.56" valueMin="1.51">1.51–1.56mm</quantity>
, TL/TW: 1.19–1.22, PL/PW: 0.26–0.29, EL/EW: 0.88–0.89, HW/PW: 0.56–0.63, PW/TW: 0.63–0.66, HW/TW: 0.38–0.40, Eye W/HW: 0.54–0.59.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,1611,2033]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">Head yellow. Pronotum, scutellar shield, and elytra bright yellow, with small dense punctures. Underside yellowish brown, except metaventrite and the middle part of the first ventrite blackish brown.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,1611,2033]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">
Body rounded, weakly convex, dosally shiny and glabrous (
<figureCitation box="[870,984,1935,1961]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1560,1584]" captionTargetBox="[160,1431,570,1528]" captionTargetId="figure-174@3.[151,1435,561,1537]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Sulcolotis threadis Liu et Wang sp. n.: a) dorsal habitus; b. lateral habitus; c. frontal habitus; d. tegmen, ventral view; e. tegmen, lateral view; f. penis; g. abdomen, male." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6876473" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6876473/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">Figs 2a–c</figureCitation>
). Head 0.39 times of elytral width (HW/ TW=1:2.6). Eyes finely faceted interocular distance 0.57 times of head width. Frons broad with punctures uniform and dense (
<figureCitation box="[278,360,2007,2033]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1560,1584]" captionTargetBox="[160,1431,570,1528]" captionTargetId="figure-174@3.[151,1435,561,1537]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Sulcolotis threadis Liu et Wang sp. n.: a) dorsal habitus; b. lateral habitus; c. frontal habitus; d. tegmen, ventral view; e. tegmen, lateral view; f. penis; g. abdomen, male." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6876473" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6876473/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">Fig. 2c</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,150,537]" pageId="3" pageNumber="78">
Pronotum 0.65 times of elytral width (PW/TW=1:1.5), moderately transverse, punctures uniform (
<figureCitation box="[1309,1422,151,177]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1560,1584]" captionTargetBox="[160,1431,570,1528]" captionTargetId="figure-174@3.[151,1435,561,1537]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Sulcolotis threadis Liu et Wang sp. n.: a) dorsal habitus; b. lateral habitus; c. frontal habitus; d. tegmen, ventral view; e. tegmen, lateral view; f. penis; g. abdomen, male." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6876473" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6876473/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="78">Figs 2a, c</figureCitation>
). Elytra with uniform and dense punctures (
<figureCitation box="[622,737,187,213]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1560,1584]" captionTargetBox="[160,1431,570,1528]" captionTargetId="figure-174@3.[151,1435,561,1537]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Sulcolotis threadis Liu et Wang sp. n.: a) dorsal habitus; b. lateral habitus; c. frontal habitus; d. tegmen, ventral view; e. tegmen, lateral view; f. penis; g. abdomen, male." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6876473" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6876473/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="78">Figs 2a–c</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,150,537]" box="[199,1247,223,249]" pageId="3" pageNumber="78">
Ventrite 6 of posterior margin at middle slightly concave and ventrite 7 subtrianglar (
<figureCitation box="[1150,1234,223,249]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1560,1584]" captionTargetBox="[160,1431,570,1528]" captionTargetId="figure-174@3.[151,1435,561,1537]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Sulcolotis threadis Liu et Wang sp. n.: a) dorsal habitus; b. lateral habitus; c. frontal habitus; d. tegmen, ventral view; e. tegmen, lateral view; f. penis; g. abdomen, male." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6876473" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6876473/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="78">
Fig. 
<quantity box="[1203,1234,223,249]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="kg" metricValue="2.0" pageId="3" pageNumber="78" unit="g" value="2.0">2g</quantity>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,150,537]" pageId="3" pageNumber="78">
Male genitalia (
<figureCitation box="[372,485,259,285]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1560,1584]" captionTargetBox="[160,1431,570,1528]" captionTargetId="figure-174@3.[151,1435,561,1537]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Sulcolotis threadis Liu et Wang sp. n.: a) dorsal habitus; b. lateral habitus; c. frontal habitus; d. tegmen, ventral view; e. tegmen, lateral view; f. penis; g. abdomen, male." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6876473" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6876473/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="78">Figs 2d–f</figureCitation>
): penis long and slender, apex pointed, penis capsule with inner arm reduced and outer arm well developed; tegmen with penis guide as long as parameres, in lateral view stout, widest at base, gradually narrowing to a pointed apex.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
